solution_04_inferential_statistics/02_confidence_intervals/04_conf_int_z_v2

video

First, determine \(z^\star\) such that \(P(|Z|<z^\star)=0.55\). It can help to draw a sketch.


The entire area under the density curve is 1. Thus, we can determine the areas of the tails (using symmetry). \[\text{area of each tail} = \frac{1-\gamma}{2} = \frac{1-0.55}{2} = 0.225\]


Determine a leftward area with boundary \(z^\star\). \[P(Z<z^\star)=\gamma + \frac{1-\gamma}{2}= 0.55+0.225=0.775\] It should be mentioned the expression can be simplified. \[P(Z<z^\star)= \frac{1}{2}+\frac{\gamma}{2}= 0.5+0.275=0.775\]


We rephrase the puzzle. We wish to determine \(z^\star\) such that \(P(Z<z^\star)=0.775\). This is easy to determine using a \(z\)-table, qnorm in R, norm.inv in spreadsheets, or other methods for evaluating the quantile function.

\[P(Z<0.76)=0.775\] In the original phrasing,

\[P(|Z|<0.76)=0.55\]

So, \(z^\star = 0.76\). Now, use the given expressions.

\[\text{Lower bound} = 26.6-(0.76)(7.5)/\sqrt{237} ~=~ 26.2\] \[\text{Upper bound} = 26.6+(0.76)(7.5)/\sqrt{237} ~=~ 27\]

Spreadsheet

A spreadsheet can use the confidence.norm function. It takes three arguments:

  • Alpha (\(\alpha\)) is the two-tail area, \(\alpha=1-\gamma=1-0.55=0.45\)
  • Population standard deviation, \(\sigma=7.5\)
  • Sample size, \(n=237\)

The function returns the margin of error. \[\text{margin of error} = \frac{z^\star \sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\]

So, in this case, if in a spreadsheet you typed =confidence.norm(1-0.55,7.5,237), the result would be the margin of error, 0.3680211. You then add/subtract the margin of error to/from the sample mean. \[\bar{x}-\text{ME} = 26.6-0.368 = 26.232\] \[\bar{x}+\text{ME} = 26.6+0.368 = 26.968\]

You can do this with a spreadsheet.


R

xbar = 26.6
sigma = 7.5
n = 237
gamma = 0.55
zstar = qnorm(gamma+(1-gamma)/2)
ME = zstar*sigma/sqrt(n)
LB = xbar-ME
UB = xbar+ME
cat(sprintf("The lower bound: %.4f\nThe upper bound: %.4f",LB,UB))
## The lower bound: 26.2320
## The upper bound: 26.9680

  1. Lower bound = \(~26.6-(0.76)(7.5)/\sqrt{237} ~=~ 26.2\)
  2. Upper bound = \(~26.6+(0.76)(7.5)/\sqrt{237} ~=~ 27\)
